    <item>
      <title>Bubble Sort</title>
      <link>https://ksu-cs-textbooks.github.io/cc310/7-searching-and-sorting/12-bubble-sort/index.html</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://ksu-cs-textbooks.github.io/cc310/7-searching-and-sorting/12-bubble-sort/index.html</guid>
      <description>Next, let&amp;rsquo;s look at another sorting algorithm, bubble sort. The basic idea behind bubble sort is to continuously iterate through the array and swap adjacent elements that are out of order. As a side effect of this process, the largest element in the array will be &amp;ldquo;bubbled&amp;rdquo; to the end of the array after the first iteration. Subsequent iterations will do the same for each of the next largest elements, until eventually the entire list is sorted.</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Bubble Sort Pseudocode</title>
      <link>https://ksu-cs-textbooks.github.io/cc310/7-searching-and-sorting/13-bubble-sort-pseudocode/index.html</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://ksu-cs-textbooks.github.io/cc310/7-searching-and-sorting/13-bubble-sort-pseudocode/index.html</guid>
      <description>To describe our bubble algorithm, we can start with these basic preconditions and postconditions.
Preconditions:
The array stores a type of elements which can be ordered. Postconditions:
The array will be sorted in ascending order. We can then represent this algorithm using the following pseudocode.
function BUBBLESORT(ARRAY)	(1) # loop through the array multiple times loop INDEX from 0 to size of ARRAY – 1	(2) # consider every pair of elements except the sorted ones loop INDEX2 from 0 to size of ARRAY – 2 – INDEX	(3) if ARRAY[INDEX2] &amp;gt; ARRAY[INDEX2 + 1] then	(4) # swap elements if they are out of order TEMP = ARRAY[INDEX2]	(5) ARRAY[INDEX2] = ARRAY[INDEX2 + 1]	(6) ARRAY[INDEX2 + 1] = TEMP	(7) end if end loop end loop end functionIn this code, we begin by looping through every element in the array, as seen on line 2.</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Bubble Sort Time Complexity</title>
      <link>https://ksu-cs-textbooks.github.io/cc310/7-searching-and-sorting/14-bubble-sort-time-complexity/index.html</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://ksu-cs-textbooks.github.io/cc310/7-searching-and-sorting/14-bubble-sort-time-complexity/index.html</guid>
      <description>Once again, let&amp;rsquo;s look at the time complexity of the bubble sort algorithm and see how it compares to selection sort.
Bubble sort is a bit trickier to analyze than selection sort, because there are really two parts to the algorithm:
The number of comparisons, and The number of swaps. Let&amp;rsquo;s look at each one individually. First, is there a way to reduce the number of comparisons made by this algorithm just by changing the input?</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Merge Sort</title>
      <link>https://ksu-cs-textbooks.github.io/cc310/7-searching-and-sorting/15-merge-sort/index.html</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://ksu-cs-textbooks.github.io/cc310/7-searching-and-sorting/15-merge-sort/index.html</guid>
      <description>Another commonly used sorting algorithm is merge sort. Merge sort uses a recursive, divide and conquer approach to sorting, which makes it very powerful. It was actually developed to handle sorting data sets that were so large that they couldn&amp;rsquo;t fit on a single memory device, way back in the early days of computing.
The basic idea of the merge sort algorithm is as follows:
If the container only contains one or two elements, we can quickly sort that container by swapping the elements if needed.</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Merge Sort Pseudocode</title>
      <link>https://ksu-cs-textbooks.github.io/cc310/7-searching-and-sorting/16-merge-sort-pseudocode/index.html</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://ksu-cs-textbooks.github.io/cc310/7-searching-and-sorting/16-merge-sort-pseudocode/index.html</guid>
      <description>Now that we&amp;rsquo;ve seen how merge sort works by going through an example, let&amp;rsquo;s look at the pseudocode of a merge sort function.
function MERGESORT(ARRAY, START, END)	(1) # base case size == 1	if END - START + 1 == 1 then	(2)	return	(3) end if	(4) # base case size == 2 if END - START + 1 == 2 then	(5) # check if elements are out of order if ARRAY[START] &amp;gt; ARRAY[END] then	(6) # swap if so TEMP = ARRAY[START]	(7) ARRAY[START] = ARRAY[END]	(8) ARRAY[END] = TEMP	(9) end if	(10) return	(11) end if	(12) # find midpoint HALF = int((START + END) / 2)	(13) # sort first half MERGESORT(ARRAY, START, HALF)	(14) # sort second half MERGESORT(ARRAY, HALF + 1, END)	(15) # merge halves MERGE(ARRAY, START, HALF, END)	(16) end function	(17)This function is a recursive function which has two base cases.</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Merge Sort Time Complexity</title>
      <link>https://ksu-cs-textbooks.github.io/cc310/7-searching-and-sorting/17-merge-sort-time-complexity/index.html</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
