    <item>
      <title>Quicksort</title>
      <link>https://ksu-cs-textbooks.github.io/cc310/7-searching-and-sorting/18-quicksort/index.html</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://ksu-cs-textbooks.github.io/cc310/7-searching-and-sorting/18-quicksort/index.html</guid>
      <description>The last sorting algorithm we will review in this module is quicksort. Quicksort is another example of a recursive, divide and conquer sorting algorithm, and at first glance it may look very similar to merge sort. However, quicksort uses a different process for dividing the array, and that can produce some very interesting results.
The basic idea of quicksort is as follows:
Choose a pivot value, called pivotValue. This value could be any random value in the array.</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Quicksort Pseudocode</title>
      <link>https://ksu-cs-textbooks.github.io/cc310/7-searching-and-sorting/19-quicksort-pseudocode/index.html</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://ksu-cs-textbooks.github.io/cc310/7-searching-and-sorting/19-quicksort-pseudocode/index.html</guid>
      <description>Now that we&amp;rsquo;ve seen an example of how quicksort works, let&amp;rsquo;s walk through the pseudocode of a quicksort function. The function itself is very simple, as shown below.
function QUICKSORT(ARRAY, START, END)	(1) # base case size &amp;lt;= 1	if START &amp;gt;= END then	(2)	return	(3) end if	(4) PIVOTINDEX = PARTITION(ARRAY, START, END)	(5) QUICKSORT(ARRAY, START, PIVOTINDEX – 1)	(6) QUICKSORT(ARRAY, PIVOTINDEX + 1, END)	(7) end function	(8)This implementation of quicksort uses a simple base case on lines 2 through 4 to check if the array is either empty, or contains one element.</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Quicksort Time Complexity</title>
      <link>https://ksu-cs-textbooks.github.io/cc310/7-searching-and-sorting/20-quicksort-time-complexity/index.html</link>
